questions.description:
```js
console.log('A: sync top');
process.nextTick(() => console.log('B: nextTick'));
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('C: promise'));
console.log('D: sync bottom');
```

questions.explanation:
The checkpoint that fires after each phase drains, in this exact priority: **`nextTick` queue first**, then the standard **microtask queue** (Promise reactions and `queueMicrotask`, together, in FIFO order).

A quick verification — the logged order is `nextTick`, `promise`, `queueMicrotask`:

```js
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('promise'));
queueMicrotask(() => console.log('queueMicrotask'));
process.nextTick(() => console.log('nextTick'));
// -> nextTick, promise, queueMicrotask
```

`setImmediate` is the impostor: it is a genuine loop **phase** (check), not a microtask, so it always waits for the loop to reach it.

questions.description:
```js
const fs = require('fs');

fs.readFile(__filename, async () => {
  setImmediate(() => console.log('immediate'));
  await null;                       // suspend here
  console.log('after-await');
  process.nextTick(() => console.log('nextTick'));
});
```

```js
function spin() {
  process.nextTick(spin); // re-queues itself forever
}
spin();
```

```js
const fs = require('fs');

fs.readFile(__filename, () => {
  setTimeout(() => console.log('timeout'), 0);
  setImmediate(() => console.log('immediate'));
});
```

```js
const start = Date.now();
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log('fired after ~' + (Date.now() - start) + 'ms');
}, 10);

// Block the only thread synchronously for ~60 ms:
const until = Date.now() + 60;
while (Date.now() < until) {}
```

```js
const fs = require('fs');

// Runs in the poll phase, as an I/O callback:
fs.readFile('./config.json', () => {
  console.log('1: config loaded');
  setTimeout(() => console.log('2: timeout'), 0);
  setImmediate(() => console.log('3: immediate'));
  process.nextTick(() => console.log('4: nextTick'));
  Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('5: promise'));
  console.log('6: handler end');
});
```

```js
const fs = require('fs');

fs.readFile(__filename, () => {
  process.nextTick(() => console.log('A: nextTick (in poll)'));
  setImmediate(() => {
    console.log('B: immediate (check)');
    process.nextTick(() => console.log('C: nextTick (after check)'));
    Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('D: promise (after check)'));
  });
  setTimeout(() => console.log('E: timeout (next timers)'), 0);
});
```

questions.explanation:
`setImmediate` schedules onto the **check** phase of a *future* loop turn, so between chunks the loop still runs **timers**, still accepts new connections in **poll**, and stays responsive. A recursive `process.nextTick` (or any recursive microtask) drains *before* the loop can advance, starving I/O — the classic freeze from the earlier question.

Verified contrast: a recursive `setImmediate` loop still let a 20 ms timer fire (after roughly 1,500 iterations on this machine); the `nextTick` version would never have let it through:

```js
let n = 0;
setTimeout(() => console.log('timer fired after', n, 'immediates'), 20);
(function loop() {
  n++;
  setImmediate(loop); // yields each turn -> the timer still gets to run
})();
```

Rule of thumb: **`setImmediate` to cooperate, `process.nextTick` to jump the queue.** For truly CPU-bound work that should not touch the loop at all, reach for a Worker thread instead.
